ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis of GQD-FA was performed by activating the carboxyl groups of GQDs with EDC and sulfo-NHS, followed by coupling the folic acid in 90 % yield (Fig. 1
                        ). The coupling yield was determined through spectrometric analysis of the folic acid in the supernatant of the reaction mixture after purification. The synthesized GQD-FA was then characterized by FTIR, PXRD AFM, and XPS (Figs. 2-5



                        ).

The attachment of the GQDs to folic acid is hypothesized to occur via the attachment of carboxyl groups on the GQDs’ edge structure to the amine groups presenting in folic acid. This occurs due to the formation of amide bonds in the presence ofsulfur-NHS and EDC, by a crosslink carbodiimide reaction which activates the GQD’s carboxyl groups [52]. The activation of functional groups from the GQD by theEDC and subsequent addition of nucleophilic species by the use of sulfo-NHS has been previously evaluated by Felix et al. [39], when the group synthesized GQD decorated with imatinib for leukemia treatment. The reaction was fully characterized and corroborated by FTIR, AFM, PXRD, and XPS analysis. Is important to notice that the diffraction pattern of GQD-Folic showed the diffraction peaks at 2θ = 26.5° and 54.6°, which correspond respectively to the (002) and (004) peaks of the graphite [53], probably a vestige from the production process. Moreover, the XPS results demonstrated that the GQD-FA is composed of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen elements. The AFM analysis showed an increase in size from the pure GQDs (13.6 nm) to GQDs-FA (25.4 nm) (Fig. 9
                     ). The increase in size corroborates the presence of folic acid on the surface of the GQDs. According to Ganganboina and Doong [54] increase in diameter clearly indicate the successful immobilization of biomolecules onto the surface nanoparticles. Also, the AFM analysis revealed a few atomic layers presented the GQDs structure, which may be meaningful for bioimaging and biomedical application [55,56]. In addition, the presence of folic acid on the surface of GQD was responsible for increasing the height of the GQD. According to Peng et al. 
                     [57], the functionalization of graphene derivates increases their size and height, with pronounced hydration of the complex due to the functional group.
